        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48483884-michael-finocchiaro?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48483884-michael-finocchiaro?shelf=art-history">art-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48483884-michael-finocchiaro?shelf=american-20th-c">american-20th-c</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2708812602" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4016314310382143532">This was a fantastic book that is highly readable for fans of art and history alike. It describes the way the world was on the cusp of modernity as we moved from the Middle Ages towards the Renaissance. It is similar to other books on the subject (Panofksy comes to mind), but this one is written a bit more with a less erudite style and yet is engaging and interesting. Highly recommended.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

